1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,069
If you live in a place where most people speak the language you are learning, you may use the language for several hours each day.

2
00:00:12,069 --> 00:00:17,320
So, it may become part of your “inner speech.”

3
00:00:17,320 --> 00:00:21,771
In other words, you start thinking in that language.

4
00:00:21,771 --> 00:00:30,213
Your mind stops trying to translate things from your native language into the second language.

5
00:00:30,213 --> 00:00:41,163
But, the majority of the VOA Learning English audience lives in places where English is not the main language.

6
00:00:41,163 --> 00:00:44,445
This may be true for you.

7
00:00:44,445 --> 00:00:49,128
You may not have many chances to practice English.

8
00:00:49,128 --> 00:00:52,312
You may even be self-taught.

9
00:00:52,312 --> 00:00:58,797
When you speak, your speech might be slower than you would like.

10
00:00:58,797 --> 00:01:08,533
This is because your mind is still translating from your first language, which can also sound unnatural.

11
00:01:08,533 --> 00:01:14,616
English, like every other language, has its own sentence structure.

12
00:01:14,616 --> 00:01:21,987
The good news is that thinking in English can bring you a huge step closer to fluency!

13
00:01:21,987 --> 00:01:28,973
It is not very difficult, but it does take conscious effort and practice.

14
00:01:28,973 --> 00:01:36,696
On today’s Education Tips, we will share some mental exercises that can help.

15
00:01:36,696 --> 00:01:41,984
Most experts note that it’s best to start small.

16
00:01:41,984 --> 00:01:48,069
So, a good first step is to think in individual words.

17
00:01:48,069 --> 00:01:57,547
Look around you. What do you see? In your head, try to name each object in your surroundings.

18
00:01:57,547 --> 00:02:06,501
Charles Thomas has taught English to Union members, children and teenagers for over 10 years.

19
00:02:06,501 --> 00:02:12,936
He has also helped open schools in several countries.

20
00:02:12,936 --> 00:02:19,539
He currently works for EF International Schools in Washington, D.C.

21
00:02:19,539 --> 00:02:27,269
Thomas tells his students to name the things that they see around them, wherever they are.

22
00:02:27,269 --> 00:02:40,299
“As you continue with this, it becomes more of a habit, so things are going to pop up into your head – computer, telephone, chair, desk. Whatever it is…wherever you are.”

23
00:02:40,299 --> 00:02:47,341
Start with nouns and then add in verbs, he suggests.

24
00:02:47,341 --> 00:02:55,717
He says you can also do this at home when you wake up and before you go to sleep.

25
00:02:55,717 --> 00:03:01,899
Teacher Andrew Hinshaw also finds this exercise helpful.

26
00:03:01,899 --> 00:03:10,824
He has been teaching English for 12 years, including in Vietnam for the U.S. Department of State.

27
00:03:10,824 --> 00:03:20,355
He currently teaches at the Carlos Rosario International Public Charter School in Washington, D.C.

28
00:03:20,355 --> 00:03:28,032
Hinshaw remembers one method some of his Vietnamese students liked.

29
00:03:28,032 --> 00:03:39,408
“I’ve had students tell me that they label everything in their room or their apartments so that these English words, kind of, stick in their heads.”

30
00:03:39,408 --> 00:03:50,699
Another exercise that both Thomas and Hinshaw suggest is describing in your mind objects you don’t know the words for.

31
00:03:50,699 --> 00:03:57,915
An example would be if you couldn't think of the word "garage,” Thomas says.

32
00:03:57,915 --> 00:04:15,853
“If you’re looking at your house and you see your garage, but you can’t think of the name in English, you can say, ‘The place inside where I put my car.’ Or you can say, ‘It’s next to my house. I keep things there.’”

33
00:04:15,853 --> 00:04:25,872
He says you can also use shorter phrases, such as “It’s similar to…” or “It’s the opposite of…”

34
00:04:25,872 --> 00:04:31,907
Hinshaw says doing this can help learners of any language.

35
00:04:31,907 --> 00:04:35,877
As a Spanish learner, he does it himself.

36
00:04:35,877 --> 00:04:41,821
The next exercise is thinking in simple sentences.

37
00:04:41,821 --> 00:04:55,035
For example, if you are sitting in a park, you can tell yourself things like, “It’s such a beautiful day” and “People are playing sports with their friends.”

38
00:04:55,035 --> 00:05:01,792
Once this becomes easy, you can move on to more difficult sentences.

39
00:05:01,792 --> 00:05:11,141
Hinshaw sometimes uses this exercise to think about what he wants to say to people in Spanish.

40
00:05:11,141 --> 00:05:22,056
“I definitely try to say these sentences in my head or try to put the words together without thinking too much about if it’s absolutely correct.”

41
00:05:22,056 --> 00:05:29,475
Another exercise experts suggest is to describe your daily activities.

42
00:05:29,475 --> 00:05:32,813
There are a few ways to do this.

43
00:05:32,813 --> 00:05:41,496
Thomas asks his beginning-level students to describe their day using the simple present verb form.

44
00:05:41,496 --> 00:05:50,648
So, they would think to themselves things like, “I put on my shirt” and “He drives the bus.”

45
00:05:50,648 --> 00:05:57,365
Other experts say you can mentally make plans in the morning when you wake up.

46
00:05:57,365 --> 00:06:04,384
This would require other verb tenses. So the skill level is a little higher.

47
00:06:04,384 --> 00:06:23,557
For example, you might tell yourself, “When I leave the house, I’m going to get an iced coffee.Then, I’ll take the train to class. I’m studying with Paola today. She said she booked a study room at the library for 2 p.m.”

48
00:06:23,557 --> 00:06:28,469
Now, let’s move to thinking in conversation.

49
00:06:28,469 --> 00:06:34,603
When you do this, you are imagining yourself speaking to someone else.

50
00:06:34,603 --> 00:06:40,112
You are asking the questions and thinking of replies.

51
00:06:40,112 --> 00:06:46,936
This is a great way to practice what you might say in a real conversation.

52
00:06:46,936 --> 00:07:05,237
For example, let’s say the imaginary person asks you a question like, “What did you think of the award show last night?” How would you answer? Imagine the conversation and practice it in your head.

53
00:07:05,237 --> 00:07:10,072
You can do this out loud or in silence.

54
00:07:10,072 --> 00:07:18,875
For all of these exercises, there will of course be words and phrases that you do not know.

55
00:07:18,875 --> 00:07:24,197
So, at some point you will need to use a dictionary.

56
00:07:24,197 --> 00:07:32,683
If your skill level is high enough, you might consider using an English-to-English dictionary.

57
00:07:32,683 --> 00:07:41,373
Hinshaw suggests writing down just five to 10 new words and phrases each day.

58
00:07:41,373 --> 00:07:50,352
Keeping a notebook, he says, helps you remember the situation that you needed that word or phrase for.

59
00:07:50,352 --> 00:07:57,024
This makes it easy to recall when you are in such a situation again.

60
00:07:57,024 --> 00:08:03,021
So, how much time should you spend on these exercises?

61
00:08:03,021 --> 00:08:07,056
Thomas says do a little every day.

62
00:08:07,056 --> 00:08:21,408
“So when you’re doing it every day, over and over again, little by little, that’s the key. Because, when you make things a habit, then it just pops up into your mind without thinking and then, before you know it, really, you’re thinking in English.”

63
00:08:21,408 --> 00:08:25,224
I'm Alice Bryant.